The given triangle has sides $2n + 12$, $3n - 3$, and $2n + 7$. Since the sides of a triangle must satisfy the triangle inequality theorem, we can set up inequalities using these side lengths to find possible values of $n$. </think> <answer> $\text{Triangle inequality theorem states that for any triangle, the sum of the lengths of any two sides must be greater than the length of the remaining side. So, we have three inequalities:}
\begin{align*}
(2n + 12) + (3n - 3) & > (2n + 7) \\
(2n + 12) + (2n + 7) & > (3n - 3) \\
(3n - 3) + (2n + 7) & > (2n + 12) \\
\end{align*}
Simplifying each inequality gives us:
\begin{align*}
5n + 9 & > 2n + 7 \\
4n + 19 & > 3n + 3 \\
5n + 4 & > 2n + 12 \\
\end{align*}
Further simplifying:
\begin{align*}
3n & > -2 \\
n & > -17 & \text{This is always true since $n$ is positive.} \\
3n & > 8 \\
\end{align*}
So, we have $n > \frac{8}{3}$, which means $n \geq 3$ since $n$ is an integer. </answer>

